WEBVTT

00:02.750 --> 00:04.685
<i>Last week on st. Elsewhere.</i>

00:04.752 --> 00:07.988
Is Reinhardt acting as
an INDIVIDUAL or as
a member of a terrorist group?

00:08.055 --> 00:10.324
- I don't know that.
- Could you give us
the name of the victim?

00:10.391 --> 00:14.929
- Katherine Mcallister.
She was in the bank.
- [ sighs ]

00:14.995 --> 00:18.799
they said there was
a bombing three days ago--
That my wife Katherine was hurt.

00:18.866 --> 00:21.101
- She's in a coma.
- Why'd you do it?

00:21.168 --> 00:23.504
You wouldn't understand.

00:23.571 --> 00:25.673
<i>This week on st. Elsewhere.</i>

00:25.739 --> 00:29.109
- and clear.
- [ beeping ]

00:29.176 --> 00:31.412
- We've got a sinus rhythm.
- You almost killed him.

00:31.478 --> 00:34.448
- I'm a psychiatrist.
- You wanna see if I'm crazy?

00:34.515 --> 00:36.517
- Are you crazy?
- Are you?

00:36.584 --> 00:40.854
- As a loon.
- Touch me again, you creep,
I'll smash your other leg!

00:40.921 --> 00:43.791
- Well, we did find
some abnormalities.
- What's wrong?

00:43.857 --> 00:46.594
It means that your child
has down's syndrome.

00:46.660 --> 00:51.599
This is our son.
This is a defective...
accident.

00:51.665 --> 00:55.936
What do you got today?
You got doctors with gym Shoes.
Gym shoes, for crying out loud!

00:56.003 --> 01:00.307
She's crazy about me. I keep
telling her it's only a sexual
relationship and nothing more.

01:00.374 --> 01:02.309
That's good.
Women are suckers
for integrity.

02:31.365 --> 02:34.568
<i>[ auschlander ]
here, the liver's
quite Healthy.</i>

02:34.635 --> 02:36.704
<i>Next.</i>

02:36.770 --> 02:39.106
<i>Now we see
numerous discrete areas
of diminished activity...</i>

02:39.173 --> 02:41.242
in Both hepatic Lobes.

02:41.308 --> 02:43.744
Next.

02:43.811 --> 02:47.381
In this biopsy,
we see the adenocarcinoma...

02:47.448 --> 02:51.585
is consistent
with the metastatic
adenocarcinoma of the Stomach.

02:51.652 --> 02:53.787
<i>Next.</i>

02:53.854 --> 02:55.956
<i>Here, we have a focus
of fat necrosis.</i>

02:56.023 --> 02:59.293
Note that some of the nuclei
have disappeared...

02:59.360 --> 03:01.228
and the cell walls
are blurred.

03:01.295 --> 03:04.098
Who took these pictures,
James Garner?

03:04.164 --> 03:06.800
May I have the lights, please?

03:09.036 --> 03:12.373
All right.

03:12.439 --> 03:14.708
You.

03:14.775 --> 03:17.278
What do I tell miss Taylor?

03:17.344 --> 03:21.448
I'm not sure.
That should ease her mind.

03:21.515 --> 03:23.484
Anyone else?

03:23.551 --> 03:28.188
Tell her the truth.
And what exactly
is the truth, Dr. Armstrong?

03:28.255 --> 03:32.393
She's dying.
Would you like to be
the one to tell her?

03:32.459 --> 03:34.461
She has a right to know.
I will if I have to.

03:34.528 --> 03:36.664
Very Good.

03:36.730 --> 03:40.401
<i>And are you going to tell her
when she's gonna die?</i>

03:40.467 --> 03:43.203
What do you mean?
Well, is she gonna die
tomorrow morning,

03:43.270 --> 03:45.205
or is she gonna die
next week?

03:45.272 --> 03:48.676
Next month? Next year?

03:48.742 --> 03:51.111
I don't know.
You don't know.

03:51.178 --> 03:55.583
It would seem that miss Taylor
is in the same predicament
we all are.

03:55.649 --> 03:58.552
We know that someday
We're gonna die.

03:58.619 --> 04:00.554
We just don't know when.

04:00.621 --> 04:03.624
[ chuckles ]
what I'm saying,
Dr. Auschlander--

04:03.691 --> 04:06.193
<i>I know what you're saying,
Dr. Armstrong.</i>

04:06.260 --> 04:10.064
<i>I'm questioning how
you would say it.</i>

04:10.130 --> 04:13.701
Let's all think about that
when we meet with miss Taylor.

04:17.971 --> 04:20.874
We're lucky to have
auschlander around
to discuss this case.

04:20.940 --> 04:24.578
Yeah, it's like Marie Antoinette
talking about the inner
mechanisms of the guillotine.

04:24.645 --> 04:26.580
No, no, no.
Franco's doing fine.

04:26.647 --> 04:29.216
What about Mr. Berman?
Did he have a good night?
Are you kidding?

04:29.283 --> 04:32.653
He was bouncing off the walls
like a Ping-Pong ball
yelling for valium.

04:32.720 --> 04:36.156
I told him yesterday
it was the valium that was
making him hypersensitive.

04:36.223 --> 04:40.794
Sometimes, we suffer from a kind
of schizophrenia around here.
I don't understand.

04:40.861 --> 04:42.796
Well, the doctors,
the nurses, the staff--

04:42.863 --> 04:44.932
We think of this hospital
as a place to work.

04:44.999 --> 04:49.103
And the interns, the residents--
They want it to be
a place to learn, of course.

04:49.169 --> 04:51.505
And the community alternates
between thinking of it...

04:51.572 --> 04:55.342
as a renaissance cathedral
or Frankenstein's castle.

04:55.409 --> 04:58.646
There's talk among the board
about closing this facility...

04:58.712 --> 05:02.349
and moving St. Eligius
to one of the better suburbs,
like Newton or Wellesley.

05:02.416 --> 05:04.518
Judge, I'm well aware
of why you're here today.

05:04.585 --> 05:07.354
That kind of talk has been
going on for a long, long time.

05:07.421 --> 05:10.357
You don't agree with the idea?
No, I don't.

05:10.424 --> 05:12.426
St. Eligius
is part of this neighborhood.

05:12.493 --> 05:16.063
It's like old mrs. Weber,
the crossing guard
at pogansett school,

05:16.130 --> 05:19.300
or that Rusty Fountain
in John Adams square.

05:19.366 --> 05:21.302
You can't take it away
without leaving a hole.

05:21.368 --> 05:23.604
[ Snoring quietly ]

05:23.671 --> 05:26.373
Dr. Osterwald, good morning.
Mm-hmm.

05:26.440 --> 05:29.476
I wouldn't want
that guy examining me.

05:29.543 --> 05:31.845
Too bad. He's the best
cardiologist in new England.

05:31.912 --> 05:33.881
Yeah?

05:38.686 --> 05:40.955
So what happened?
I called sanitation.

05:41.021 --> 05:43.958
Well, they didn't hear you.
We had another kid in here
last night.

05:44.024 --> 05:46.660
Twelve years old.
All right,
I'll call 'em again.

05:46.727 --> 05:49.263
Yeah, make sure you do.
Damn hospital!

05:49.330 --> 05:52.466
Angry young man.
Yes, that's Rooney.
He's an orderly.

05:52.533 --> 05:55.703
You let an orderly
talk to you like that?
He's talking about syringes.

05:55.769 --> 05:58.372
You see, sanitation can't
dispose of them fast enough,

05:58.439 --> 06:00.040
and the kids pick them up
and use them again.

06:00.107 --> 06:02.176
You mean the children
are junkies?

06:02.243 --> 06:04.211
Afraid So.

06:06.046 --> 06:09.183
Next time, try ringing
the doorbell, hmm?

06:09.250 --> 06:12.519
You've got that terrorist guy
Reinhardt in here, haven't you?

06:12.586 --> 06:15.856
Right.
And the woman that was in the
bank when the bomb went off?

06:15.923 --> 06:18.759
Katherine Mcallister.
How is she?

06:18.826 --> 06:21.929
Alive.
Shall we?

06:24.798 --> 06:27.501
Listen up, Barbara.
I'm not gonna give you
any more demerol.

06:27.568 --> 06:30.004
I'm not gonna give you
any more percodan.
If you want drugs,

06:30.070 --> 06:33.040
then you just go on out
on the street and buy 'em
like everybody else does.

06:33.107 --> 06:35.175
There's a call for you
on line two.
It's your wife.

06:35.242 --> 06:38.545
What does she want?
She wants to know if you've got
the ticket for the laundry.

06:38.612 --> 06:42.049
What ticket?
She's your wife, pal.

06:42.116 --> 06:44.285
I'll be right back.

06:47.454 --> 06:50.157
Touch me again,
you little creep,
I'll smash your other leg!

06:50.224 --> 06:52.159
<i>[ Woman on P.A. ]
will the owner
of the blue ford...</i>

06:52.226 --> 06:57.398
<i>blocking the ambulance entrance
move it immediately.</i>

06:57.464 --> 07:02.269
<i>The owner of a blue ford,
you're blocking
the ambulance entrance.</i>

07:02.336 --> 07:04.772
<i>Move it immediately.</i>

07:04.838 --> 07:08.709
I don't know what you've got,
Fiscus, but if you could
freeze-Dry it, you'd be rich.

07:08.776 --> 07:11.845
Well, cover for me tomorrow,
and I'll give you the secret.
What's tomorrow?

07:11.912 --> 07:15.549
Cathy and I are going
to the pistol range.
You're fantastic.

07:15.616 --> 07:17.818
You've got a date
with Cathy Martin, you're
going to the pistol range.

07:17.885 --> 07:21.789
She's a sharpshooter.
Yeah, I'll bet she is.

07:21.855 --> 07:24.058
[ Chuckles ]
Victor,

07:24.124 --> 07:26.594
I got a secret
between you and me,
all right?

07:30.464 --> 07:32.600
All we ever do
is have Sex.

07:32.666 --> 07:35.336
It's sex, sex, Sex.

07:35.402 --> 07:37.571
My heart bleeds for you.
She's crazy about me.

07:37.638 --> 07:40.841
I keep telling her
it's only a sexual relationship
and nothing more.

07:40.908 --> 07:42.876
That's good.
Women are suckers
for integrity.

07:42.943 --> 07:47.047
I don't want her to get
too serious, or it'll ruin it.
You know what I mean.

07:47.114 --> 07:50.451
But I gotta tell you,
between my double shifts here
and her, I'm drained.

07:50.517 --> 07:53.821
Kind of like a Maple tree
After sap-Sucking season.

07:53.888 --> 07:55.990
Yeah, right.
Sure.

07:56.056 --> 07:59.360
So when you suggested
a more mundane activity,
she suggested--

07:59.426 --> 08:01.562
the pistol range.
Exactly. Sex and violence.

08:01.629 --> 08:03.898
It's the american way.
Will you cover for me?

08:03.964 --> 08:06.100
You got it.
Thanks a lot.

08:06.166 --> 08:09.270
<i>[ girl ]
it's my turn!</i>

08:09.336 --> 08:11.272
It's my turn!
It's my turn!

08:11.338 --> 08:14.341
Girls, girls, girls. Stop that.
We're gonna leave for school
in five minutes,

08:14.408 --> 08:16.343
and I want
all that food gone.

08:16.410 --> 08:18.512
Now, eat.
Why didn't mom
make breakfast?

08:18.579 --> 08:21.682
She's, uh, sleeping late.

08:21.749 --> 08:24.318
Is she sick?
No.

08:24.385 --> 08:28.188
Then why's she still sleeping?
She's gonna have a baby.

08:28.255 --> 08:31.592
I know that!
A little brother.

08:31.659 --> 08:33.594
Right, daddy?
Right.

08:33.660 --> 08:37.565
Not necessarily.
Good morning.

08:37.631 --> 08:42.736
A big, strong boy
to protect you from, uh,
all the other big, strong boys.

08:42.803 --> 08:44.772
Right?

08:46.507 --> 08:48.475
Hungry?

08:50.344 --> 08:53.213
I've got news for you.
Even if this one's a girl,
we're stopping.

08:53.280 --> 08:56.083
I'm gettin' too old for this.

08:56.150 --> 08:58.452
- Give me a "B."
- [ together ]
"B!"

08:58.519 --> 09:01.855
What if the test says "Girl"?
give me an "O."

09:01.922 --> 09:04.792
- [ together ]
"O!"
- Stubborn.

09:04.858 --> 09:07.161
Your father is the most
stubborn man in massachusetts.

09:07.228 --> 09:09.496
<i>And give me a "Y."
[ together ]
"Y!"</i>

09:09.563 --> 09:13.334
- What does it spell?
- Boy, boy, boy!

09:17.404 --> 09:19.974
<i>[ Knocking ]</i>

09:22.610 --> 09:25.980
how you doin'?
I'm Dr. Beale.

09:26.046 --> 09:28.749
Somebody just examined me.

09:28.816 --> 09:30.851
I'm a psychiatrist.

09:32.553 --> 09:36.924
I didn't ask to see you.
No, no, you did not.

09:36.991 --> 09:40.294
But I'm afraid you don't
have much choice either.

09:40.361 --> 09:42.863
You wanna see if I'm crazy?

09:42.930 --> 09:44.765
That's what they pay me for.

09:46.267 --> 09:48.202
How are you gonna find out?

09:48.269 --> 09:51.672
Well, I figure
the best way...

09:51.739 --> 09:55.876
is just to come out
and ask you.

09:55.943 --> 09:58.045
- Are you crazy?
- Are you?

09:58.112 --> 10:02.616
As a loon. Why else
would I be a psychiatrist?

10:02.683 --> 10:06.120
Of course,
we're a little reluctant
to use the word "Crazy."

10:06.186 --> 10:09.857
It's a little vague,
you know.

10:09.924 --> 10:13.093
Says in here that you're
a pretty bright Fella.

10:13.160 --> 10:17.097
Honor Student.
Top of your class
till you dropped out.

10:17.164 --> 10:21.235
- What is the, um,
Douglas Sterner award?
- Science.

10:21.302 --> 10:23.270
Science?

10:23.337 --> 10:26.540
Well, then you and me,
we got something
in common, don't we?

10:26.607 --> 10:28.742
I doubt it.

10:28.809 --> 10:32.613
You know, there's been
something gnawing at me.

10:32.680 --> 10:34.848
Maybe you can
help me out.

10:34.915 --> 10:37.918
For christmas,
I got this sweater.

10:37.985 --> 10:42.389
Had a V-Neck,
100% cotton, size large.

10:42.456 --> 10:45.726
And by mistake,
my cleaning lady,
Erma Castro,

10:45.793 --> 10:48.262
she put it into
the washing machine.

10:48.329 --> 10:51.565
When I got it out,
I couldn't even fit it
over my arm.

10:51.632 --> 10:56.670
<i>Now, my question is,
where did all that cotton go?</i>

10:58.305 --> 11:03.277
You're a real down-Home
good old boy, aren't ya?

11:04.378 --> 11:06.347
Yeah, I guess.

11:08.883 --> 11:12.386
You, uh--
You play chess, huh?

11:12.453 --> 11:14.421
Yeah.

11:16.123 --> 11:19.026
You know, I've been playin'
with a guy named Dr. Craig.

11:19.093 --> 11:23.163
He's a surgeon,
and these surgeons only
play chess but a few ways.

11:23.230 --> 11:26.834
<i>Once they get somethin'
stuck in their head,
it's there forever.</i>

11:26.901 --> 11:29.303
You and me'll play.

11:30.671 --> 11:33.340
<i>Dr. Pig?</i>

11:33.407 --> 11:36.644
I don't trust you at all.

11:38.746 --> 11:42.349
You know, they say
that paranoids make
the very best chess players,

11:42.416 --> 11:44.485
<i>because with every move,</i>

11:44.552 --> 11:47.955
they naturally assume
that their opponent
is out to get 'em.

11:50.824 --> 11:54.361
In this lab, we do
a lot of experimentation
with endocrine Therapy.

11:54.428 --> 11:56.697
Playing around with hormones,
speeding up the rate of growth,

11:56.764 --> 11:58.699
that sort of thing.

11:58.766 --> 12:00.701
It's pretty Interesting.

12:00.768 --> 12:03.837
Over here, we study the tissues
that we take from the animals.

12:03.904 --> 12:07.074
Um-- Hello.

12:07.141 --> 12:09.143
Message from Upstairs.

12:13.581 --> 12:15.516
[ laughing ]

12:15.583 --> 12:17.484
Belznik's starting to snap.

12:19.386 --> 12:22.223
Seems to me this tube System's
a little out-Of-Date.

12:22.289 --> 12:24.358
Yes, well, it's the only wing
that still has it, judge.

12:24.425 --> 12:26.827
When we get some more money--
Say no more.
Say no more.

12:26.894 --> 12:28.796
Thank you.

12:32.199 --> 12:34.335
Hi. Hi.

12:34.401 --> 12:36.570
We used to get them
from the pound
until they took it to court.

12:36.637 --> 12:40.474
Now we're paying a supply house
four times what we were
donating to the S.P.C.A.

12:40.541 --> 12:43.310
Do you kill them?
Some, yes.

12:43.377 --> 12:47.648
I have three pedigree show Dogs.
Well, Mrs. Beardsley,
this is a hospital.

12:47.715 --> 12:49.984
People run it.
People are born here.

12:50.050 --> 12:51.986
They come here when
they're hurt or sick.

12:52.052 --> 12:56.156
Some die, and some,
with a little luck,
get better.

12:56.223 --> 12:58.225
What does that have to do
with These poor animals?

12:58.292 --> 13:00.394
Do you know anyone
with diabetes?

13:00.461 --> 13:02.396
Yes, my sister-In-Law Marian.

13:02.463 --> 13:05.199
It's very likely she wouldn't
be alive today if it weren't
for the experiments...

13:05.266 --> 13:08.068
in Insulin therapy conducted
in labs like this using Dogs.

13:08.135 --> 13:10.871
Even so, there's got
to be a better way.

13:10.938 --> 13:13.540
If you find one,
we'll try it.

13:15.409 --> 13:17.378
There you go.

13:22.149 --> 13:24.885
Bon Voyage.

13:28.255 --> 13:30.524
<i>Please sit down.</i>

13:38.432 --> 13:40.367
Before we did
the amniocentesis,

13:40.434 --> 13:43.737
remember we talked about
the kinds of things
we'd be looking for--

13:43.804 --> 13:48.242
how the fluid around the fetus
would indicate if there were
any metabolic abnormalities.

13:50.244 --> 13:52.279
Well, we did find
some abnormalities.

13:52.346 --> 13:55.049
What's wrong?

13:55.115 --> 13:58.152
The 21st chromosome
split into three instead of two.

13:58.219 --> 14:01.388
You see, There are
23 matching pair--
What does this mean?

14:03.023 --> 14:05.092
It means that your child
has down's syndrome.

14:11.632 --> 14:14.368
Are you positive?
Yes.

14:17.004 --> 14:21.141
Doctor, um,
let me ask you something.

14:21.208 --> 14:25.746
In this test, isn't there--
isn't there a lot
of margin for error?

14:25.813 --> 14:30.117
Believe me, Mr. Whitehill,
I wouldn't have told you
unless I was sure.

14:33.921 --> 14:36.490
Well, I'm-I'm not sure I--

14:38.125 --> 14:42.263
the thing
I don't understand is--

14:42.329 --> 14:44.265
How retarded will the baby be?

14:44.331 --> 14:47.334
That's hard to say exactly.

14:47.401 --> 14:51.138
Some Down's children
live Well Into their 20s.
But they are children forever.

14:51.205 --> 14:54.842
The average mental age
is about seven years old,

14:54.909 --> 14:56.911
though some do
considerably Better.

14:58.946 --> 15:01.181
Will the baby
be deformed?

15:01.248 --> 15:03.551
There's a high risk of
some sort of Deformity.

15:03.617 --> 15:06.220
Arched palate, slanted eyes.

15:06.287 --> 15:09.990
God.
I know right now it seems
like the end of the world.

15:10.057 --> 15:15.229
But down's children
are very happy, very special.

15:15.296 --> 15:18.465
- Many parents find
immense pleasure in raising--
- pleasure?

15:20.301 --> 15:22.670
Dr. Cavanero,

15:22.736 --> 15:27.575
the thing
I don't understand is,
what caused this?

15:27.641 --> 15:29.577
We have two perfectly
healthy children.

15:29.643 --> 15:32.980
There's nothing wrong
with either of you.
It's not hereditary.

15:33.047 --> 15:37.251
Sometimes,
it-It just happens.

15:37.318 --> 15:40.354
Uh, Dr. Cavanero,
thank you very much.

15:40.421 --> 15:43.023
I think, Um--

15:43.090 --> 15:45.059
Thank you.

15:46.961 --> 15:49.230
I'd like to give you the number
of a friend of mine...

15:49.296 --> 15:51.498
who works at
a genetic counseling center
at the north end.

15:58.005 --> 16:01.008
- What sex is the baby?
- It's a boy.

16:18.492 --> 16:22.429
Did you have a nice visit
from your sister?
Yeah.

16:22.496 --> 16:25.032
She brought you
a new perfume.

16:25.099 --> 16:27.735
Called "Naughty nights."

16:27.801 --> 16:30.104
Very pleasant.

16:30.170 --> 16:33.207
Feel how lobulated she is.

16:38.812 --> 16:42.249
[ loudly ] does that hurt?
I ain't deaf,
and I ain't senile either.

16:42.316 --> 16:45.352
Gently, gently,
like this.

16:45.419 --> 16:48.923
Easy. That's it.
There we are.

16:48.989 --> 16:50.958
Now you.

16:53.661 --> 16:55.896
Breathe in, please.

16:55.963 --> 16:57.932
Breathe out.

16:59.433 --> 17:01.635
There's a vertical span
of about 20 centimeters.

17:01.702 --> 17:04.838
I see your Ivy's Thriving.

17:04.905 --> 17:07.808
Somebody's sneaking in here
waterin' that plant.

17:10.778 --> 17:13.513
All you young folks
gonna be doctors?

17:13.580 --> 17:16.517
- We are doctors.
- Don't look old enough.

17:16.584 --> 17:19.486
Don't let their
freshly scrubbed faces fool you.

17:21.088 --> 17:24.224
How have you been feeling?

17:24.290 --> 17:26.859
Doc, I've been spittin' up
some green stuff.

17:26.926 --> 17:30.598
We'll give you some medicine
to calm your stomach.
Anything else we can get you?

17:32.399 --> 17:35.536
You can leave
one of these young,
good-Looking doctors here.

17:35.603 --> 17:37.538
[ laughter ]
see you later.

17:44.612 --> 17:47.314
Her liver was hard as a rock.
What treatment
would you suggest?

17:47.381 --> 17:49.316
Radiation therapy.

17:49.383 --> 17:54.989
It may relieve some tension,
